<subSubSection id="CA6BA35E584679038A11C79D2375CFC8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8AD75453BA0C6F6063BDD33C41247C7B" pageNumber="25">
Ants in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="946E2EC774EC04A75A53D5159D67EC02" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2336" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Amblyopone" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Amblyopone Erichson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amblyopone</taxonomicName>
have cryptic foraging habits and are specialist predators on geophilomorph centipedes and other arthropods living in soil or rotten wood. Two species are known from California: 
<taxonomicName id="B4D04523E7161EF5F4C0D6FAF9AFD3F8" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25202" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Amblyopone" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Amblyopone oregonensis (Wheeler)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oregonensis">A. oregonensis (Wheeler)</taxonomicName>
is found in shaded, medium-elevation coniferous forests in northern California, while 
<taxonomicName id="F16A17EF094A7585436A644C08A1E0B7" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25204" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Amblyopone" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Amblyopone pallipes (Haldeman)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallipes">A. pallipes (Haldeman)</taxonomicName>
is widespread in chaparral and low elevation woodland.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B4597FE81543013A683CCF93B0DC778A" pageNumber="25">Species identification: Ward (1988). Additional references: Brown (1960a), Creighton (1940b), Haskins (1928), Lattke (1991d), Lacau and Delabie (2002), Traniello (1978, 1982).</paragraph>
